{"key":"processedPost-9124142","value":{"id":9124142,"first":9122802,"last":9124142,"when":1224822498,"utime":"10/24/08 07:28 AM","content":"By the way, I've always said plain verm is the worst possible choice for a casing layer, and as for the nutrition, it has very little, but definitely has <i>some</i> or cobweb and trich wouldn't grow on it, and mycelium wouldn't colonize it so fast.<br /><br />I've tried the brf tek with many substitutes for vermiculite, and so far, nothing comes even close.&nbsp; I've used sand, sandy loam, peat moss, ground perlite, sawdust, compost, coffee grinds, seaweed, and a few I can't remember right now.&nbsp; Even with wood decomposing species, a 50/50 mix of verm and sawdust in the brf tek is superior to brown rice and sawdust alone.<br /><br />The point is that verm isn't inert and needs to be treated as such.&nbsp; It's not something to argue about, just something to understand and take into account.<br />RR","title":"Re: What's More Nutritional?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}